                                                               PIC18F-Based IoT Development Board with Wi-Fi Connectivity and Analog Signal Conditioning
Abstract
The PIC18F-Based IoT Development Board is a versatile embedded hardware platform designed for sensor interfacing, data acquisition, wireless communication, and industrial monitoring applications. The system integrates a PIC18F microcontroller, ESP8266 Wi-Fi module, LM358-based analog signal conditioning circuits, LCD display interface, digital I/O expansion, and multiple communication protocols such as UART, SPI, and I²C. The board is powered through a 24V industrial input and generates regulated 5V and 3.3V supplies for onboard components. The platform enables real-time monitoring, local display, and wireless transmission of sensor data, making it suitable for IoT, automation, and educational applications.
1. Introduction
Embedded systems play a crucial role in modern industrial automation, smart monitoring, and Internet of Things (IoT) applications. Conventional development boards often require multiple external modules for wireless communication, sensor conditioning, and display interfacing. This project addresses these limitations by integrating all essential components into a single PCB platform.
The developed board combines analog signal acquisition, wireless connectivity, user interface components, and industrial-grade power management. It serves as a complete solution for developing IoT-based monitoring and control systems.
2. Objectives
•	Design a compact PIC18F-based development board.
•	Integrate ESP8266 Wi-Fi connectivity.
•	Provide analog signal conditioning for sensor interfacing.
•	Support multiple communication protocols.
•	Enable real-time display of system information.
•	Facilitate industrial monitoring and automation applications.
•	Develop a reusable platform for embedded system projects.
3. System Components
3.1 PIC18F Microcontroller
The PIC18F microcontroller acts as the central processing unit. It performs:
•	Sensor data acquisition
•	Analog-to-digital conversion
•	Communication management
•	Display control
•	Alarm generation
•	System monitoring
3.2 ESP8266 Wi-Fi Module
The ESP-01 module provides wireless communication capabilities. It enables:
•	Remote monitoring
•	Cloud connectivity
•	IoT integration
•	Wireless data transmission
3.3 LM358 Signal Conditioning Circuit
LM358 operational amplifiers are used to amplify and condition low-level sensor signals before ADC conversion.
Benefits include:
•	Improved measurement accuracy
•	Noise reduction
•	Enhanced sensitivity
3.4 LCD Display
The display provides:
•	Real-time sensor readings
•	System status information
•	Network connection status
•	Alert messages
3.5 Power Supply Section
The board accepts a 24V DC industrial input and generates:
•	5V using MC7805 regulator
•	3.3V using AMS1117 regulator
Protection components include:
•	Fuse
•	Varistor
•	Filtering inductor
4. Hardware Design
The PCB consists of the following functional blocks:
Power Management Block
Responsible for voltage regulation and protection.
Microcontroller Block
Controls all processing and communication activities.
Analog Interface Block
Interfaces external sensors through LM358 amplifiers.
Communication Block
Supports:
•	UART
•	SPI
•	I²C
Wireless Communication Block
Provides Wi-Fi connectivity through ESP8266.
User Interface Block
Includes LCD display, LEDs, and buzzer.
5. Working Principle
1.	The board receives a 24V DC supply.
2.	Voltage regulators generate 5V and 3.3V rails.
3.	The PIC18F initializes all peripherals.
4.	Sensor signals enter through analog input channels.
5.	LM358 amplifiers condition the sensor signals.
6.	ADC converts analog values into digital data.
7.	Processed data is displayed on the LCD.
8.	Data is transmitted through the ESP8266 Wi-Fi module.
9.	LEDs and buzzer indicate system status and alarms.
